Add the boiling water to a large #saucepan{} with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and bring to
the boil. When boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g} and boil for ~{8-10%minutes}
before draining in a #sieve{} and returning to the pan with the lid on, off the heat.

Meanwhile halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).
Trim the @green beans{150%g} then chop into thirds. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Heat a splash of @oil{splash} in a #frying pan{} or #wok{} over medium-high heat. Add the
onion and stir-fry until starting to soften, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the @beef strips{240%g} and
stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in the @rendang paste{1} and @thai garnish{1}(aromatic) and
cook for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the green beans and @coconut milk{200%ml}, bring to a simmer and cook, with the
lid on (or some foil), stirring occasionally, until thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Season the rendang with @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste.

Serve the rice in #bowls{} topped with the rendang and a sprinkle of chopped coriander. Enjoy!

> We've looked to Indonesia for inspiration for this quick and easy curry dish. On the table
> in just 20 minutes but still bursting with flavour, tender strips of beef are fried with
> an aromatic thai garnish and rendang paste, before being gently simmered in coconut milk.
> Served with fluffy coconut basmati rice, the green beans and coriander perfectly round off
> the dish with a splash of colour.